Chapter 2 code and analysis

section 1

Analysis of student 2014

  • First I produced the needed subset of the original data. #Johdatus yhteiskuntatilastotieteeseen, syksy 2014 (Introduction to Social Statistics, fall 2014 - in Finnish), international survey of Approaches to Learning from http://www.helsinki.fi/~kvehkala/JYTmooc/JYTOPKYS3-data.txt Dataset contains the variables gender, age, attitude, deep, stra, surf and points by combining questions in the learning2014 data and excludes observations where the exam points variable is zero.

Deep learning questions are like this: " I usually set out to understand for myself the meaning of what we have to learn." Surface learning exercises are like this: " I find I have to concentrate on just memorising a good deal of what I have to learn." Strategic learning exercies are like this: " I think Im quite systematic and organised when it comes to revising for exams."

learning2014 <- read.csv("/Users/Tuomassoila/IODS-project/data/data1.csv")

Part 4

Even with this adjustment the model is quite poor in explaining the points gotten. The Adjusted R-squared value is only 0.1446, which means that the model can only explain 14.5% of the variability around the mean.

part 5

Then I produced the following diagnostic plots:Residuals vs Fitted values, Normal QQ-plot and Residuals vs Leverage.

par(mfrow = c(2,2)) # sets the plot in same image
plot(my_model, which=c(1,2,5)) #draws the plot number: 1,2,5 bt which command from the plot list

When the normal Q-Q plot is examined we can see that the normality there is some doubt about the normality since the lower and upper part does fit really well on the linear line.

On the residuals vs.fitted the distribution is reasonably random so the size of the errors do not depend on the explanatory variables.

Residuals vs leverage reveald which observations have the highest impact. In the plot we can see there are no single values that have and unausally high impact on the model.

Section 3

Relationship between chosen variables and alcohol consumption

I have chosen four variables: famrel - quality of family relationships, age, studytime - weekly study time and G3 - final grade. My hypothesis is that all of these have an affect on high alcohol consumption, so that people with lower family relations quality drink more = negative effect, older students drink more = positive effect, children who study less drink more, and student with lower grades drink more.

Then I produced the fitted logistic regression model with the variables chosen earlier.

# find the model with glm()
m <- glm(high_use ~ age + famrel+ studytime + G3, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# print out a summary of the model

From the output we can see that age, famrel and studytime are statistically significant with P values less than 0.05. From this we can conclude that these variables have predictive power over high alcohol consumption. But Final grade is not statistically significant. Aging increases possibility of more alcohol consumption (0.21512), better family relations lower the odds of high alcohol consumption (-0.29036) and longer studytime has the same effect (-0.60967 ).

Odds rations: I produced the odd ratios for the model.

m <- glm(high_use ~ age + famrel+ studytime + G3, data = alc, family = "binomial")
# compute odds ratios (OR)
OR <- coef(m) %>% exp

# compute confidence intervals (CI)
CI <- confint(m)%>% exp
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
# print out the odds ratios with their confidence intervals
cbind(OR, CI)
##                    OR       2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.1095809 0.002902035 3.9454163
## age         1.2400146 1.015519368 1.5211442
## famrel      0.7479955 0.585125417 0.9540464
## studytime   0.5435274 0.396981377 0.7303409
## G3          1.0065312 0.957469303 1.0593549

From this we can conclude that age has positive affect on alcohol consumption since the Odds ratio is higher than 1. Family relations have a negative effect on alcohol consumption and so does studytime. Age seems to have a positive effect but it is not statistically significant ( 1 fits in the confidence interval 0.957469303 1.0593549).

section 6

Now I will try if my model will predict correct answers against the actual data. I produced the confusion matrix, which according to Wikipedia works like this: Each column of the matrix represents the instances in a predicted class while each row represents the instances in an actual class (or vice versa).

library(dplyr)

# fit the model
m <- glm(high_use ~ age + famrel+ studytime, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability>0.5)

# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   258   12
##    TRUE    101   11

From the confusion matrix we can gather that my model produced 258 correct Falses for high alcohol consumption, 12 false falses for low non-high alcohol consumption. 101 false True occurrences of high alcohol consumption and 11 true cases of high alcohol consumption.

Then I calculated the training error for my model. And if understood correctly tested it against just guessing that everyone has low alcohol consumption and the results seem that guessing works better.

# (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# loss function called with the desired attributes
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2958115
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = 0)
## [1] 0.2931937

section 7

I calculated the 10-fold cross validation on my model and the prediction error but not by much ( original = 0.2958115 and 10-fold = 0.2905759)

library(boot)
cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m, K = 10)

# average number of wrong predictions in the cross validation
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2984293

#Drawing the lda biplot with arrows 
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 10, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "purple", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0,
         x1= myscale * heads[,choices[1]],
         y1= myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col = color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col = color, pos = 3)
}

# target classes as numeric 
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)
#plotting the lda
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1 )

In the LDA the linear discriminant 1 (LD1) explain 94% of the variance between groups.
In the LDA biplot we have the classes in different colour and the variables in the middle. The direction and length of the arrow displays how the variable impacts the model and these are based on the coefficients. So as the Rad variable coefficient is quite big (2.97683720) it is clearly visible in the visualisation as well.

part 6

I saved the crime categories from the test set and removed the categorical crime variable from the test dataset. Then I predicted the classes with the LDA model on the test data. I cross tabulated the results with the crime categories on the test set.

The prediction seems to be reasonable. The predictions are partly quite accurate at least for high and fairly good for med_low class. For other classes the predictions are not as good with quite a lot of wrong predictions.

#saving the correct classes from the test data 
correct_classes <- test$crime

part 7

I standardised the Boston dataset and ran the k-means algorithm on the set. I visualised the clusters with the pairs function. It would seem that two clusters would an optimal solution in this case since the drop is the steepest at this point. Based on the pairs visualisation it seems that at least rad and tax are good discriminatory variables.

library(MASS)
#accessing the data
data("Boston")
#scaling the data 
boston_scaled <- scale(Boston)
#calculating the euclidian distances of the observations.
dist_eu <- dist(boston_scaled)

#adding the max number of clusters first 15 and then 2 as this was the optimal. 
k_max <- 2
# calculating the total with sum of squares 
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(dist_eu, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualising the results 
plot(1:k_max, twcss, type='b')

# running the k-means clustering
km <-kmeans(dist_eu, centers = 2)

#plotting the scaled_boston dataset with clusters

pairs(Boston, col = km$cluster)
